prompt:
At the vigil for Aboriginal schoolboy Cassius Turvy at Town Hall last night, Greens Senator David Schubridge said that he wished there were more people from federal parliament at the vigils listening and hearing powerful truths. Do you agree that there should have been greater attendance from politicians?

###
completion: I think that the thieving of Cassius' life is one of those moments I think where it makes all of us pause and wonder whether we are doing enough. I wasn't at the vigil this morning. I'm told that one of the frankly stunning moments about it was when Cassius' family were behaving with incredible grace given what they've been through. And so I think we should acknowledge that too. We should acknowledge that we've got a long way to go as a country still despite all the progress that we've made. And if your question is whether or not Cassius' death makes me and my colleagues understand that more needs to be done than the answer is yes. END

prompt:
There is a vote looming on a Voice to Parliament and Noel Pearson, one of the advocates for the Voice said in his lectures that Aboriginal and Torres Strait Island people are the most unloved people in Australia. Why are they so unloved? 

###
completion: I mean, it's unacceptable if that's the case. Those lectures were, you know, characteristically thoughtful and impactful and powerful. And again, you know, we need to listen to the First Nations people of this country, not just listen but act. The Voice is a crucial part of that in my opinion, but not just that. There is so much more that we need to do and our government is committed to doing more. END
